post_text:
Sharing an excerpt from the statement our board president read last night:

The La Mesa-Spring Valley School District is committed to the realization of equity and social justice within our schools. We stand together with those who have suffered violence at the hands of racism and oppression, and we are committed to ensuring that each and every one of our students is valued and loved. As we move through these devastating times in our community, we reaffirm our ongoing commitment to ensuring equity in our schools. We are actively engaged in this ongoing work, to affirm the unbounded worth and potential of all children. We continue to partner with San Diego State University and the San Diego County Office of Education in an effort to examine and implement equitable practices in our schools. We are committed to ending the inequities that exist because of the history of exclusion, discrimination, segregation, and systemic racism in our nation‚Äôs educational system.

As we move through these devastating times in our community, we reaffirm our ongoing commitment to ensuring equity in our schools. We are actively engaged in this ongoing work, to affirm the unbounded worth and potential of all children. We continue to partner with San Diego State University and the San Diego County Office of Education in an effort to examine and implement equitable practices in our schools. We are committed to ending the inequities that exist because of the history of exclusion, discrimination, segregation, and systemic racism in our nation‚Äôs educational system.

post_text:
Dear LMSV Families,

Many have asked whether schools will be able to reopen on April 13th. Earlier today we sent out an update to share what we know at this time. Here is an excerpt:

"As long as the statewide ‚Äústay at home‚Äù order remains in place, and as long as county health restrictions on gatherings and social distancing remain in place, our schools will remain closed. Please be assured that we will inform you right away if health orders are lifted and we are able to reopen. In the meantime, we should all be prepared for the real possibility that health orders will remain in place well beyond spring break and that schools will not be able to reopen on April 13. In the spirit of planning for the worst but hoping for the best, we are developing a distance learning plan for all students in the event that our schools must remain closed beyond April 13."

You can read the entire update here:
https://www.lmsvschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/3-30-20-Parent-Letter.pdf

Mr. Hale's math problem of the day!

1. A man in Tennessee bought 18,000 bottles of hand sanitizer for approximately $5.97 each. He sold 300 bottles for $20 a piece before all the sites where he could list them shut him down. First question: if he had been able to sell all 18,000 bottles for $20, how much "profit" would he have made? Second question: Now that this troll is stuck with all these bottles, how much money is he going to lose?

Although there are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in La Mesa-Spring Valley Schools, out of an abundance of caution and in consultation with California Public Health Officials, LMSV will close all schools in a statewide effort to prevent the spread of COVID-19.

School will remain open today with regular dismissal procedures. Schools will be closed beginning Monday, March 16 through the end of spring break. At this time, we expect to reopen school on Monday, April 13. Additional details will be provided later today. Visit our webpage www.lmsvschools.org/coronavirus for updates.
